[Patient] Can you give me tips for managing my fluid intake with heart failure?
[Educator] Limit salt intake, track fluids consumed, and watch for signs of fluid overload.
[Patient] How can I track my fluid intake without spending a lot of money?
[Educator] Use measuring cups or household items to measure fluids. Look for low-cost alternatives.
[Patient] What signs should I watch for to know if I have too much fluid?
[Educator] Look for swelling in legs, shortness of breath, and sudden weight gain.
[Patient] How much fluid should I be drinking each day to manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Aim for around 2 liters of fluid per day, but follow your healthcare provider's recommendations.
[Patient] Can I still drink coffee and other beverages with heart failure?
[Educator] Limit caffeine and alcohol intake, as they can affect fluid balance in the body.
[Patient] How can I remember to track my fluid intake every day?
[Educator] Set reminders on your phone, keep a journal, or ask a family member to help.
[Patient] Are there any foods I should avoid that can make my heart failure worse?
[Educator] Avoid high-sodium foods like processed meats, canned soups, and fast food.
[Patient] What should I do if I notice any signs of fluid overload?
[Educator] Contact your healthcare provider immediately and follow their instructions.
[Patient] Is it normal to feel thirsty all the time with heart failure?
[Educator] Excessive thirst can be a sign of fluid imbalance, so monitor your fluid intake closely.
[Patient] Can I still exercise with heart failure, and how does it affect my fluid intake?
[Educator] Light exercise is beneficial, but monitor your fluid intake before, during, and after.
[Patient] How can I tell if I am getting enough fluids without drinking too much?
